5000|$|Although {{the term}} [...] "induction cut" [...] is {{generally}} {{used to refer}} to male military haircuts, females also endure a form of an induction haircut, <b>in</b> that <b>their</b> <b>hair</b> may be trimmed to chin-length. The concept of an [...] "induction haircut" [...] has also been the focus of litigation, such {{as in the case of}} The Citadel where attorneys for the first female cadet, Shannon Faulkner, argued that the [...] "knob haircut" [...] (referring to the college's freshman class's traditional nickname) would [...] "implement rules which altogether denigrate Ms. Faulkner's identity as a woman." ...|$|R
